    "The proposed Rs 3 Cr Marcellus PMS allocation passes regulatory and product-quality stress tests but fails structural mandate stress on three simultaneous boundary conditions. Under Scenario 1 (timing), the deployment lands inside the case decision window with no headroom for adverse market drift: post-action equity prints 71.7 percent against a 70 percent ceiling on the trade date itself, meaning a single quarter of equity outperformance or debt drawdown pushes the breach wider rather than the deliberation finding the breach narrowing into compliance through passage of time. Under Scenario 2 (concentration), three layers of concentration develop simultaneously, single-position concentration at 16.7 percent of liquid AUM against the 15 percent standard ceiling, look-through sector concentration at 75 percent in the top-two sectors (Financials 34 percent, FMCG 41 percent), and wrapper-level concentration moving from one PMS to two PMS with style overlap that the evidence layer flags but does not resolve. None of these are individually unbounded; the compound is the issue.",
